Adaptive multipatch with Clustering methods¶

Giuseppe Puglisi - (2020/02/07)

in collaboration with Davide Poletti and Josquin Errard

In this posting we briefly summarize several tests performed with FGbuster in the branch adaptive under development.
The outline is to check whether implementing patches defined with Clustering methodologies helps or not in decreasing the systematics residuals we see. In previous posting i've shown how to define the patches via clustering methodologies.

In this posting we want to get closer to more realistic case, including a more complete sky model ( with both thermal dust and synchrotron with varying spectral indices) and noise in the data.

Simulation setup :

  • sky : d1s1 (encoding only dust component with varying $\beta_d$ and $T_d$.
  • instrument : Litebird Frequency channels config ( same as the ones Josquin's been working on)
  • components: we fit both for CMB, synchrotron and dust and check the residuals on the CMB component.

Finally we compare the outputs from two different component separation routines: the one performed within patches defined with Clustering methodologies (assuming spectral parameters constant within each patch), and the simplistic method which fits for one single spectral parameters across the full sky .

Loading cluster defined patches¶

For each spectral parameter we perform the clustering analysis to identify patches. This is performed by estimating the Hellinger similarity pairwise pixel -by-pixel, the value of the parameter at a given pixel and its uncertainties are required to estimate how similar two pixels are. Uncertainties are taken from Commander Dust map. For $\beta_s$ uncertainties are estimated as inversely proportional to the intensity map of the lowest frequency channel. Maps are downgraded at nside=32.

Below you can find the maps:

Combining multiple cluster maps into one with Pairing functions¶

So far with FGBuster, is not possible to perform a run with adaptive comp.sep with multiple maps of patches (one per spctral parameters). We therefore have to combine the three maps (in fig.1) into one by means of a Pairing Function.

A Pairing function is a process to uniquely encode two natural numbers into a single natural number. Any pairing function can be used in set theory to prove that integers and rational numbers have the same cardinality as natural numbers. In theoretical computer science they are used to encode a function defined on a vector of natural numbers $ f:\mathbb {N} ^{r}\rightarrow \mathbb {N} $ into a new function $ g:\mathbb {N} \rightarrow \mathbb {N} $. In our case $r=2$, i.e. we are looking for a bijection to map $f : \mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N} \rightarrow \mathbb {N}$. The Cantor Pairing Function is essentially what we need, and it's defined as : $$f(n,m) :=\frac{ (n+m )(n+m+1)}{2} + m$$

We therefore define the combined cluster with the Cantor pairing function.

as in this reference: $$\langle \beta_s, \beta_d, T_d \rangle = \langle \beta_s, \langle \beta_d, T_d \rangle \rangle$$

cantor_func = lambda n,m : pl.int_( (n+m )*(n+m+1)/2  + m) 

idpatches =cantor_func(Tdclust,cantor_func(Bdclust,Bsclust ))
idpatches[~Galmask]=19
hp.mollview(idpatches, fig=133 , cmap=pl.cm.Spectral, norm='hist')

freqs=  pl.array(instrument.Frequencies)

for i in range(freqs.shape[0]): 
    cov[i,0,:]*=(instrument.Sens_I[i] )**2/hp.nside2resol(nside, arcmin=True)
    cov[i,1,:]*=(instrument.Sens_P[i] )**2/hp.nside2resol(nside, arcmin=True)
cov[:,2,:]= cov[:,1,:]

Increasing pixels in the map¶

We can upgrade the map of the patches to a higher nside, in order to see what's the leakage at higher multipoles.

In principle, one should obtain the patches from the map of $\beta_d,T_d, \beta_s$ at the nside the analysis is done, from that get the optimal number of patches and perform the component separation. However, this is very time consuming being the cluster similarity estimated pairwise, the computational cost is $\mathcal{O}(N_{pix}^2)$.

We therefore upgrade the map of patches (fig.1) at nside=128 and run fgbuster on maps (signal +noise ) at the same nside .
